## Real-World Load Balancer Technologies

### Nginx
The most popular open-source load balancer and reverse proxy.
```nginx
upstream backend {
    least_conn;
    server backend1.example.com weight=3;
    server backend2.example.com;
    server backend3.example.com backup;
}

server {
    listen 80;
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://backend;
    }
}
```

### HAProxy
High-performance TCP/HTTP load balancer. Used by GitHub, Reddit, Stack Overflow.
```
frontend http_front
    bind *:80
    default_backend servers

backend servers
    balance roundrobin
    server server1 10.0.0.1:80 check
    server server2 10.0.0.2:80 check
    server server3 10.0.0.3:80 check
```

### AWS Load Balancers
| Type | Layer | Best For |
|------|-------|----------|
| ALB (Application) | L7 | HTTP/HTTPS, microservices |
| NLB (Network) | L4 | Ultra-high performance, TCP/UDP |
| CLB (Classic) | Both | Legacy, avoid for new projects |

### Interview Tip
Mention specific technologies! Saying "I'd use Nginx as a reverse proxy with least-connections algorithm" is much stronger than "I'd use a load balancer."

## Core Gateway Functions

### 1. Request Routing
Route requests to the correct backend service based on URL path, headers, or query parameters.

```
GET /api/users/123     → User Service
POST /api/orders       → Order Service
GET /api/products      → Product Service
```

### 2. Authentication & Authorization
Verify JWT tokens, API keys, or OAuth tokens BEFORE the request reaches any service.

```typescript
// Gateway middleware
async function authenticate(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.split(' ')[1];
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'No token' });

  try {
    const user = jwt.verify(token, SECRET);
    req.user = user;
    next(); // Proceed to service
  } catch {
    res.status(403).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });
  }
}
```

### 3. Rate Limiting
Prevent abuse by limiting requests per user/IP.
```
User A: 100 requests/minute → OK
User A: 101st request → 429 Too Many Requests
```

### 4. Request/Response Transformation
Modify requests before forwarding and responses before returning.
```
Client sends: { "user_name": "alice" }
Gateway transforms to: { "userName": "alice" }  (camelCase for internal APIs)
```

### 5. Load Balancing
Distribute requests across multiple instances of each service.

### 6. Circuit Breaking
If a service is down, return a cached/default response instead of cascading failure.

## Rate Limiting at the Gateway

Rate limiting protects your services from abuse and ensures fair usage.

### Token Bucket Algorithm
Imagine a bucket that holds tokens. Each request consumes a token. Tokens refill at a fixed rate.

```typescript
class TokenBucket {
  private tokens: number;
  private lastRefill: number;

  constructor(private capacity: number, private refillRate: number) {
    this.tokens = capacity;
    this.lastRefill = Date.now();
  }

  tryConsume(): boolean {
    this.refill();
    if (this.tokens >= 1) {
      this.tokens -= 1;
      return true; // Request allowed
    }
    return false; // Rate limited
  }

  private refill() {
    const elapsed = (Date.now() - this.lastRefill) / 1000;
    this.tokens = Math.min(this.capacity, this.tokens + elapsed * this.refillRate);
    this.lastRefill = Date.now();
  }
}
```

### Distributed Rate Limiting
With multiple gateway instances, you need a shared counter (Redis):
```typescript
async function checkRateLimit(userId: string): Promise<boolean> {
  const key = `rate:${userId}:${Math.floor(Date.now() / 60000)}`; // Per minute
  const count = await redis.incr(key);
  if (count === 1) await redis.expire(key, 60);
  return count <= 100; // 100 requests per minute
}
```

### Rate Limit Headers
```
X-RateLimit-Limit: 100
X-RateLimit-Remaining: 42
X-RateLimit-Reset: 1640000000
```
Always tell clients their limits — good API design.

## Circuit Breaker at the Gateway

What happens when a downstream service is slow or down? Without protection, the gateway keeps sending requests, overwhelming both itself and the failing service.

### The Circuit Breaker Pattern
Like an electrical circuit breaker — when too many failures occur, it 'opens' and stops sending requests.

```
Closed (normal) → failures exceed threshold → Open (blocking)
Open → timeout expires → Half-Open (testing)
Half-Open → test succeeds → Closed (normal)
Half-Open → test fails → Open (blocking)
```

```typescript
class CircuitBreaker {
  private failures = 0;
  private state: 'closed' | 'open' | 'half-open' = 'closed';
  private lastFailure = 0;

  async call(fn: () => Promise<any>) {
    if (this.state === 'open') {
      if (Date.now() - this.lastFailure > 30000) {
        this.state = 'half-open'; // Try one request
      } else {
        throw new Error('Circuit is open — service unavailable');
      }
    }

    try {
      const result = await fn();
      this.failures = 0;
      this.state = 'closed';
      return result;
    } catch (err) {
      this.failures++;
      this.lastFailure = Date.now();
      if (this.failures >= 5) this.state = 'open';
      throw err;
    }
  }
}
```

### Fallback Strategies
When the circuit is open:
- Return cached data (stale but available)
- Return a default response
- Return a degraded response (e.g., hide recommendations but still show products)

## Caching Anti-Patterns

### Mistake 1: Caching Everything
Not all data benefits from caching. If data is accessed once and never again, caching wastes memory.
**Rule**: Only cache data with a high read-to-write ratio.

### Mistake 2: No TTL
Cache entries without TTL live forever, eating memory and serving stale data.
**Fix**: Always set a TTL, even if it's long (24 hours).

### Mistake 3: Cache Stampede
1000 requests arrive. Cache entry just expired. All 1000 hit the database simultaneously.
```typescript
// BAD: Every request during cache miss hits DB
const data = await cache.get(key) || await fetchFromDB(key);

// GOOD: Mutex lock — only one request fetches
const data = await cache.get(key);
if (!data) {
  const lock = await acquireLock(key);
  if (lock) {
    const freshData = await fetchFromDB(key);
    await cache.set(key, freshData);
    releaseLock(key);
  } else {
    // Wait for the lock holder to populate cache
    await sleep(100);
    return cache.get(key);
  }
}
```

### Mistake 4: Large Cache Values
Storing entire API responses in cache. If the response is 1MB, you're wasting cache memory.
**Fix**: Cache only the expensive-to-compute parts.

### Mistake 5: Not Monitoring Cache Hit Rate
If your cache hit rate is below 80%, your cache is probably misconfigured.
**Monitor**: hit rate, miss rate, eviction rate, memory usage.

## Query Optimization

The difference between a 50ms query and a 5-second query is usually optimization, not hardware.

### The EXPLAIN Plan
```sql
EXPLAIN ANALYZE
SELECT u.name, COUNT(o.id) as order_count
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN orders o ON o.user_id = u.id
WHERE u.created_at > '2024-01-01'
GROUP BY u.name
ORDER BY order_count DESC
LIMIT 10;
```

### Common Optimization Patterns

**1. Use indexes on WHERE and JOIN columns**
```sql
CREATE INDEX idx_orders_user_id ON orders(user_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_users_created ON users(created_at);
```

**2. Avoid SELECT ***
```sql
-- BAD: fetches all columns
SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 5;
-- GOOD: fetch only what you need
SELECT name, email FROM users WHERE id = 5;
```

**3. Use pagination**
```sql
-- BAD: loads ALL results into memory
SELECT * FROM products ORDER BY created_at;
-- GOOD: cursor-based pagination
SELECT * FROM products WHERE id > 1000 ORDER BY id LIMIT 20;
```

**4. Avoid N+1 queries**
```typescript
// BAD: 1 query + N queries
const users = await db.query('SELECT * FROM users');
for (const user of users) {
  user.orders = await db.query('SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = ?', user.id);
}

// GOOD: 2 queries total
const users = await db.query('SELECT * FROM users');
const orders = await db.query('SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id IN (?)', userIds);
```

## Consensus — The Problem of Agreement

Consensus is the problem of getting a group of processes to agree on a single value, even when some processes crash or messages are delayed. It is provably impossible in a fully asynchronous system with even one faulty node (FLP impossibility, 1985). Real systems work around this with timeouts.

### Why Paxos Is Not Used Directly

Paxos (Lamport, 1989) solves consensus but is famously hard to implement correctly. Raft (Ongaro & Ousterhout, 2014) was designed to be **understandable** — same guarantees, clearer decomposition.

## Raft in Detail

Raft decomposes consensus into three sub-problems:

1. **Leader election** — choose one authoritative node
2. **Log replication** — leader appends, followers copy
3. **Safety** — no two leaders in the same term, committed entries never lost

### Leader Election

Every node starts as a **Follower**. If it receives no heartbeat within its **election timeout** (randomised 150–300 ms), it becomes a **Candidate** and requests votes.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Follower
    Follower --> Candidate: election timeout fires
    Candidate --> Leader: receives majority votes
    Candidate --> Follower: discovers higher term
    Leader --> Follower: discovers higher term
    Leader --> Leader: sends heartbeats every 50ms
```

**Vote granting rules**:
- A node votes for a candidate only if the candidate's log is at least as up-to-date as its own
- A node votes for at most one candidate per term
- A candidate needs votes from floor(n/2) + 1 nodes (majority)

```python
from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from typing import Optional
import random

@dataclass
class RaftNode:
    node_id: str
    peers: list
    current_term: int = 0
    voted_for: Optional[str] = None
    state: str = "follower"
    log: list = field(default_factory=list)
    votes_received: set = field(default_factory=set)
    election_timeout: float = field(
        default_factory=lambda: random.uniform(0.15, 0.30)
    )

    def start_election(self) -> dict:
        self.current_term += 1
        self.state = "candidate"
        self.voted_for = self.node_id
        self.votes_received = {self.node_id}
        last_log_index = len(self.log) - 1
        last_log_term = self.log[-1]["term"] if self.log else 0
        return {
            "type": "RequestVote",
            "term": self.current_term,
            "candidate_id": self.node_id,
            "last_log_index": last_log_index,
            "last_log_term": last_log_term,
        }

    def handle_vote_response(self, granted: bool, from_node: str):
        if granted:
            self.votes_received.add(from_node)
        majority = len(self.peers) // 2 + 1
        if len(self.votes_received) >= majority:
            self.state = "leader"
            print(f"Node {self.node_id} elected leader for term {self.current_term}")
            print(f"Votes: {self.votes_received} (needed {majority} of {len(self.peers)+1})")

node = RaftNode("A", peers=["B", "C", "D", "E"])
vote_req = node.start_election()
print(f"Election started: term={vote_req['term']}")
node.handle_vote_response(True, "B")
node.handle_vote_response(True, "C")  # now has 3/5 — majority
```

### Log Replication

Once elected, the leader accepts client writes and replicates them:

```typescript
interface LogEntry {
  term: number;
  index: number;
  command: string;
}

class RaftLeader {
  private log: LogEntry[] = [];
  private commitIndex = 0;
  private matchIndex: Map<string, number>;
  private currentTerm: number;
  private followers: string[];

  constructor(followers: string[], term: number) {
    this.followers = followers;
    this.currentTerm = term;
    this.matchIndex = new Map(followers.map(f => [f, -1]));
  }

  appendEntry(command: string): number {
    const entry: LogEntry = {
      term: this.currentTerm,
      index: this.log.length,
      command,
    };
    this.log.push(entry);
    console.log(`Entry at index=${entry.index} pending commit (need majority ACK)`);
    return entry.index;
  }

  onFollowerACK(followerId: string, matchIndex: number): boolean {
    this.matchIndex.set(followerId, matchIndex);
    const replicated = [...this.matchIndex.values()].filter(i => i >= matchIndex).length;
    const majority = Math.floor((this.followers.length + 1) / 2) + 1;
    if (replicated >= majority - 1) {
      this.commitIndex = matchIndex;
      console.log(`Committed index=${matchIndex}`);
      return true;
    }
    return false;
  }
}
```

### Safety Guarantee

Raft guarantees: if two logs contain an entry with the same index and term, the logs are **identical** in all entries up through that index. A new leader can only be elected if it has **all committed entries**.

### Practical Numbers

| Parameter | Typical Value | Effect |
|-----------|--------------|--------|
| Election timeout | 150–300 ms (randomised) | Prevents simultaneous elections |
| Heartbeat interval | 50 ms | Must be << election timeout |
| Leader election time | 150–300 ms | Recovery speed after leader failure |
| etcd throughput (3-node DC) | ~10,000 writes/sec | p99 < 1 ms |

## Split-Brain and How Raft Prevents It

In Raft, split-brain cannot happen in the same term because a node can only vote once per term and two majorities cannot exist simultaneously in a cluster of n nodes.

```mermaid
graph LR
    subgraph "5-node cluster — network partition"
        subgraph "Partition A (3 nodes)"
            A["Node A — Leader term 5"]
            B["Node B — Follower"]
            C["Node C — Follower"]
        end
        subgraph "Partition B (2 nodes)"
            D["Node D — Candidate (cannot get majority)"]
            E["Node E — Follower"]
        end
    end
    style A fill:#27ae60,color:#fff
    style D fill:#e74c3c,color:#fff
```

## Interview Q&A

**Q: How long does Raft leader election take?**
A: Typically one election timeout interval: 150–300 ms. With randomised timeouts, the probability of a split vote requiring multiple rounds is low (< 10% in practice).

**Q: What happens to writes during leader election?**
A: They are rejected (the cluster is unavailable for writes for the election duration). This is the CP choice.

**Q: What is a "term" in Raft?**
A: A monotonically increasing logical clock. Each election attempt starts a new term. Terms are used to detect stale leaders — if a node receives a message with a higher term, it immediately reverts to follower.

## The Problem with Physical Clocks in Distributed Systems

Physical clocks on different machines drift. Even with NTP, clocks across servers typically differ by **1–100 ms**, and during NTP re-sync they can jump backwards. This means you cannot use wall-clock timestamps alone to establish the order of events across machines.

**Lamport timestamps** (1978) give a partial ordering: if event A causes event B, then `timestamp(A) < timestamp(B)`. But two concurrent events can have equal or inverted Lamport timestamps.

**Vector clocks** (Fidge/Mattern, 1988) track causality per-node, enabling you to determine if two events are causally related or truly concurrent.

## Vector Clock Algorithm

Each node maintains a vector of counters — one per node in the system:

- On local event: increment own counter
- On send: attach current vector clock
- On receive: merge (take max of each entry), then increment own counter

```python
from typing import Dict
from dataclasses import dataclass
import copy

@dataclass
class Message:
    sender: str
    payload: str
    vector_clock: Dict[str, int]

class VectorClockNode:
    def __init__(self, node_id: str, all_nodes: list):
        self.node_id = node_id
        self.vc: Dict[str, int] = {n: 0 for n in all_nodes}

    def tick(self):
        self.vc[self.node_id] += 1

    def local_event(self, description: str):
        self.tick()
        print(f"[{self.node_id}] local: {description} VC={self.vc}")

    def send(self, payload: str) -> Message:
        self.tick()
        msg = Message(self.node_id, payload, copy.deepcopy(self.vc))
        print(f"[{self.node_id}] send: '{payload}' VC={msg.vector_clock}")
        return msg

    def receive(self, msg: Message):
        for node, ts in msg.vector_clock.items():
            self.vc[node] = max(self.vc[node], ts)
        self.tick()
        print(f"[{self.node_id}] recv from {msg.sender} VC={self.vc}")

    @staticmethod
    def compare(vc_a: Dict[str, int], vc_b: Dict[str, int]) -> str:
        a_le_b = all(vc_a[k] <= vc_b[k] for k in vc_a)
        b_le_a = all(vc_b[k] <= vc_a[k] for k in vc_b)
        if a_le_b and b_le_a:
            return "equal"
        elif a_le_b:
            return "a happens-before b"
        elif b_le_a:
            return "b happens-before a"
        else:
            return "concurrent (conflict!)"

nodes = ["A", "B", "C"]
A = VectorClockNode("A", nodes)
B = VectorClockNode("B", nodes)
C = VectorClockNode("C", nodes)

A.local_event("write x=1")   # A: {A:1, B:0, C:0}
msg1 = A.send("x=1")          # A: {A:2, B:0, C:0}
B.receive(msg1)                # B: {A:2, B:1, C:0}
B.local_event("write y=2")   # B: {A:2, B:2, C:0}

C.local_event("write x=99")  # C: {A:0, B:0, C:1} — concurrent!

vc_b = {"A": 2, "B": 2, "C": 0}
vc_c = {"A": 0, "B": 0, "C": 1}
print(VectorClockNode.compare(vc_b, vc_c))  # concurrent (conflict!)
```

## Conflict Detection

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant A
    participant B
    participant C
    Note over A,C: Initial state: all {A:0,B:0,C:0}
    A->>A: write(x=1) VC={A:1,B:0,C:0}
    A->>B: replicate(x=1)
    B->>B: recv VC={A:1,B:1,C:0}
    C->>C: write(x=99) VC={A:0,B:0,C:1}
    Note over B,C: B and C have CONCURRENT writes — conflict!
    B->>C: sync
    C->>C: detect conflict and resolve
```

### Version Vectors vs Vector Clocks

- **Vector clock**: tracks causality of events at each node
- **Version vector**: tracks causality of a specific key's versions (per-replica)

```typescript
type VersionVector = Record<string, number>;

function dominates(a: VersionVector, b: VersionVector): boolean {
  return Object.keys(b).every(k => (a[k] ?? 0) >= b[k]);
}

function concurrent(a: VersionVector, b: VersionVector): boolean {
  return !dominates(a, b) && !dominates(b, a);
}

const v1: VersionVector = { nodeA: 3, nodeB: 1 };
const v2: VersionVector = { nodeA: 2, nodeB: 2 };
console.log(concurrent(v1, v2)); // true — must resolve conflict
```

## Practical Overhead

Vector clocks scale **O(n)** with the number of nodes:

| Cluster Size | Vector Clock Size |
|--------------|------------------|
| 10 nodes | 80 bytes (8-byte int × 10) |
| 100 nodes | 800 bytes |
| 1,000 nodes | 8 KB — prohibitive per-message |

Solutions: **dotted version vectors** (Riak 2.0), **interval tree clocks**, or limiting replication to a fixed number of replicas (DynamoDB uses 3).

## Interview Q&A

**Q: Can vector clocks tell you which concurrent write is "correct"?**
A: No. Vector clocks detect conflicts but do not resolve them. Resolution requires application logic: LWW, CRDTs, or user-facing conflict resolution.

**Q: Why does Cassandra use timestamps instead of vector clocks?**
A: Operational simplicity. Vector clocks require coordination on node additions/removals. Cassandra bets on NTP keeping skew < 1 ms and accepts the rare LWW error as a trade-off.

**Q: What is a "dotted version vector"?**
A: An optimisation that avoids false conflicts by also tracking which specific value was written, not just the version count. Used in Riak 2.0+.

## Hybrid Logical Clocks — The Production Solution

Vector clocks scale O(n) with node count, which becomes prohibitive in large clusters. **Hybrid Logical Clocks (HLC)**, used by CockroachDB and YugabyteDB, combine physical time with Lamport logical time:

- Causal ordering (like Lamport)
- Close to physical time (within epsilon of NTP)
- O(1) space — a single 64-bit timestamp per event

```python
import time
from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass
class HLCTimestamp:
    wall: int    # physical time (milliseconds since epoch)
    logical: int  # logical counter for same-millisecond events

    def to_int(self) -> int:
        return (self.wall << 16) | self.logical

class HybridLogicalClock:
    def __init__(self):
        self.last = HLCTimestamp(wall=0, logical=0)

    def now(self) -> HLCTimestamp:
        physical_ms = int(time.time() * 1000)
        if physical_ms > self.last.wall:
            self.last = HLCTimestamp(wall=physical_ms, logical=0)
        else:
            self.last = HLCTimestamp(wall=self.last.wall, logical=self.last.logical + 1)
        return HLCTimestamp(wall=self.last.wall, logical=self.last.logical)

    def update(self, received: HLCTimestamp) -> HLCTimestamp:
        physical_ms = int(time.time() * 1000)
        new_wall = max(physical_ms, received.wall, self.last.wall)
        if new_wall == self.last.wall == received.wall:
            new_logical = max(self.last.logical, received.logical) + 1
        elif new_wall == self.last.wall:
            new_logical = self.last.logical + 1
        elif new_wall == received.wall:
            new_logical = received.logical + 1
        else:
            new_logical = 0
        self.last = HLCTimestamp(wall=new_wall, logical=new_logical)
        return self.last

node_a = HybridLogicalClock()
node_b = HybridLogicalClock()
t1 = node_a.now()
t2 = node_b.update(t1)
print(f"Causal order preserved: {t2.to_int() > t1.to_int()}")  # True
```

HLC timestamps are human-readable (close to wall clock), debuggable, and can be used for time-based partitioning and TTL calculations — advantages vector clocks do not have. For systems with fewer than 50 nodes, vector clocks remain the conceptually cleaner choice; above 50 nodes, HLC is the practical production standard.

### Summary: Choosing a Clock Mechanism

| Mechanism | Space | Causality | Physical Meaning | Best For |
|-----------|-------|-----------|-----------------|----------|
| Physical timestamps | O(1) | No | Yes | Simple systems, accept rare errors |
| Lamport timestamps | O(1) | Partial | No | Total ordering, simple causality |
| Vector clocks | O(n) | Full | No | Small clusters, full conflict detection |
| HLC | O(1) | Full | Close | Production distributed DBs |

## Failure Modes in Distributed Systems

### Taxonomy of Failures

| Type | Description | Example |
|------|-------------|--------|
| Crash-stop | Node stops and never returns | Server kernel panic |
| Crash-recovery | Node stops, restarts with durable state | Rebooted database |
| Omission | Node drops some messages | Network buffer overflow |
| Byzantine | Node sends arbitrary/malicious messages | Bit-flip corruption, adversary |

Most production systems assume **crash-recovery** failures (not Byzantine). Byzantine fault tolerance requires **3f+1** nodes to tolerate **f** traitors.

## Quorum Reads and Writes

For **N** replicas with **W** write quorum and **R** read quorum:

- `W + R > N` guarantees you see the latest write (overlap ensures at least one fresh replica)
- `W > N/2` prevents two concurrent writes from both getting quorum

```python
class QuorumCalculator:
    def __init__(self, n: int):
        self.n = n

    def is_strong_consistency(self, r: int, w: int) -> bool:
        return r + w > self.n

    def max_tolerable_write_failures(self, w: int) -> int:
        return self.n - w

    def max_tolerable_read_failures(self, r: int) -> int:
        return self.n - r

    def summary(self, r: int, w: int):
        print(f"N={self.n}, R={r}, W={w}")
        print(f"  Strong consistency: {self.is_strong_consistency(r, w)}")
        print(f"  Max write failures: {self.max_tolerable_write_failures(w)}")
        print(f"  Max read failures: {self.max_tolerable_read_failures(r)}")

q = QuorumCalculator(5)
q.summary(r=3, w=3)
# N=5, R=3, W=3 → Strong consistency: True, Max write failures: 2

q.summary(r=1, w=5)
# N=5, R=1, W=5 → Strong consistency: True, Max write failures: 0
# ALL writes must succeed — zero failure tolerance for writes

q.summary(r=1, w=1)
# N=5, R=1, W=1 → Strong consistency: False (eventual only)
```

### Common Quorum Configurations

| Config | R | W | Use Case |
|--------|---|---|----------|
| Quorum/Quorum | ceil(N/2)+1 | ceil(N/2)+1 | Strong consistency, balanced |
| ONE/ALL | 1 | N | Fast reads, slow writes |
| ALL/ONE | N | 1 | Fast writes, slow reads |
| ONE/ONE | 1 | 1 | Eventual only, max performance |

## The Gossip Protocol

Gossip (epidemic protocol) is used by Cassandra, Consul, and Dynamo for cluster membership and failure detection without a central coordinator.

**Properties**:
- **Convergence time**: O(log N) rounds — a cluster of 1,000 nodes converges in ~10 gossip rounds
- **Bandwidth**: each node gossips to k random peers per round (k=3 typical)
- **Failure detection**: Cassandra marks a node "down" after missing heartbeats for phi_convict_threshold (default: 8 = ~10 seconds)

```typescript
interface NodeState {
  nodeId: string;
  generation: number;      // incremented on restart
  heartbeatVersion: number; // incremented every second
  status: "UP" | "DOWN" | "LEAVING" | "JOINING";
}

class GossipNode {
  private nodeId: string;
  private clusterView: Map<string, NodeState>;
  private heartbeat = 0;

  constructor(nodeId: string) {
    this.nodeId = nodeId;
    this.clusterView = new Map();
    this.clusterView.set(nodeId, {
      nodeId,
      generation: Date.now(),
      heartbeatVersion: 0,
      status: "UP",
    });
  }

  tick(): void {
    this.heartbeat++;
    this.clusterView.get(this.nodeId)!.heartbeatVersion = this.heartbeat;
  }

  merge(received: NodeState[]): number {
    let updates = 0;
    for (const state of received) {
      const existing = this.clusterView.get(state.nodeId);
      if (!existing ||
          state.generation > existing.generation ||
          (state.generation === existing.generation &&
           state.heartbeatVersion > existing.heartbeatVersion)) {
        this.clusterView.set(state.nodeId, state);
        updates++;
      }
    }
    return updates;
  }
}
```

## Hinted Handoff and Anti-Entropy

When a replica is down during a write, the coordinating node stores a **hint** — a temporary copy of the write. When the down node returns, the hint is replayed.

**Merkle trees** (anti-entropy): Cassandra compares hash trees of data ranges between replicas to efficiently find divergent segments without transferring all data.

```python
import hashlib

class MerkleNode:
    def __init__(self, data: bytes | None = None):
        self.data = data
        self.left = None
        self.right = None
        self.hash = self._compute_hash()

    def _compute_hash(self) -> str:
        if self.data is not None:
            return hashlib.sha256(self.data).hexdigest()
        left_hash = self.left.hash if self.left else ""
        right_hash = self.right.hash if self.right else ""
        return hashlib.sha256((left_hash + right_hash).encode()).hexdigest()

def find_divergent_ranges(node_a: MerkleNode, node_b: MerkleNode) -> list:
    if node_a.hash == node_b.hash:
        return []  # Subtrees identical
    if node_a.data is not None:
        return ["this_range_diverged"]
    divergent = []
    if node_a.left and node_b.left:
        divergent += find_divergent_ranges(node_a.left, node_b.left)
    if node_a.right and node_b.right:
        divergent += find_divergent_ranges(node_a.right, node_b.right)
    return divergent
```

## Interview Q&A

**Q: With N=3, W=2, R=2 — if two nodes crash after a write, can I read the data?**
A: The write succeeded (2 of 3 ACKed). Only 1 node remains. R=2 requires 2 nodes, so reads will fail. The data is durable but unavailable until a node recovers.

**Q: What is split-brain in a database cluster?**
A: Two partitions each believe they are the authoritative master and accept writes independently. Quorum prevents this — two partitions cannot both get majority with odd N. Always use 3, 5, or 7 nodes.

**Q: How fast does gossip converge in a 1,000-node cluster?**
A: With 1-second intervals and O(log N) rounds, convergence takes ~10 seconds. Cassandra's phi-accrual detector adds ~10 more seconds before declaring a node down — total ~20 seconds detection time.

## Phi Accrual Failure Detector — Cassandra in Practice

Cassandra does not use a simple timeout-based failure detector (which generates false positives under load). It uses the **phi accrual failure detector** (Hayashibara et al., 2004), which outputs a continuous suspicion level rather than a binary up/down signal.

```python
import math, time
from collections import deque

class PhiAccrualDetector:
    def __init__(self, window_size: int = 200, threshold: float = 8.0):
        self.arrival_intervals: deque = deque(maxlen=window_size)
        self.threshold = threshold  # Cassandra default: 8.0
        self.last_heartbeat = None

    def heartbeat(self):
        now = time.monotonic()
        if self.last_heartbeat is not None:
            interval_ms = (now - self.last_heartbeat) * 1000
            self.arrival_intervals.append(interval_ms)
        self.last_heartbeat = now

    def phi(self) -> float:
        if len(self.arrival_intervals) < 2 or self.last_heartbeat is None:
            return 0.0
        elapsed_ms = (time.monotonic() - self.last_heartbeat) * 1000
        mean = sum(self.arrival_intervals) / len(self.arrival_intervals)
        variance = sum((x - mean)**2 for x in self.arrival_intervals) / len(self.arrival_intervals)
        std_dev = math.sqrt(variance) if variance > 0 else 1.0
        y = (elapsed_ms - mean) / std_dev
        e = math.exp(-y * (1.5976 + 0.070566 * y * y))
        cdf = 1.0 - (1.0 / (1.0 + e)) if elapsed_ms > mean else 1.0 / (1.0 + e)
        return -math.log10(1 - cdf) if cdf < 1 else 16.0

    def is_suspected_down(self) -> bool:
        return self.phi() >= self.threshold
```

The phi threshold of 8 corresponds to a false positive rate of 10^-8. With 1-second heartbeats, phi reaches 8 approximately **10 seconds** after the last heartbeat — significantly reducing false positives compared to a simple 1-second timeout.

### Quorum Availability Under Multiple Failures

For a 5-node Cassandra cluster with RF=3 and quorum W=2, R=2:

| Nodes Failed | Writes Available? | Reads Available? | Notes |
|-------------|------------------|-----------------|-------|
| 0 | Yes | Yes | Normal operation |
| 1 | Yes | Yes | 4/5 nodes up, quorum=2 still reachable |
| 2 | Yes | Yes | 3/5 nodes up, still meets quorum |
| 3 | No | No | Only 2 nodes left, cannot reach quorum=2 for both W and R simultaneously |
| 4 | No | No | Only 1 node, no quorum possible |

Key insight: with RF=3 and quorum=2, you can tolerate exactly **floor((RF-1)/2) = 1** simultaneous node failure while maintaining strong consistency. Hinted handoff + read repair covers transient failures of additional nodes — but only for eventual consistency reads/writes.

## CRDTs — Conflict-Free Replicated Data Types

CRDTs (Shapiro et al., 2011) are data structures that can be replicated across nodes and merged automatically, **always producing a consistent result regardless of the order or concurrency of operations**.

The key insight: if all operations are **monotonically increasing** (they only move in one direction), then merging is just taking the maximum — no coordination, no conflicts, ever.

### Two Flavours of CRDTs

| Type | Full Name | How it works |
|------|-----------|-------------|
| **CvRDT** | Convergent (state-based) | Send full state; merge = join (LUB) |
| **CmRDT** | Commutative (op-based) | Send operations; ops must be commutative |

## G-Counter (Grow-Only Counter)

Each node tracks its own increment count. The global value is the sum of all nodes' counts. Merging takes the max per node — perfectly safe to apply in any order.

```python
from typing import Dict

class GCounter:
    def __init__(self, node_id: str, all_nodes: list):
        self.node_id = node_id
        self.counts: Dict[str, int] = {n: 0 for n in all_nodes}

    def increment(self, amount: int = 1):
        self.counts[self.node_id] += amount

    def value(self) -> int:
        return sum(self.counts.values())

    def merge(self, other: "GCounter") -> "GCounter":
        result = GCounter(self.node_id, list(self.counts.keys()))
        for node in self.counts:
            result.counts[node] = max(self.counts[node], other.counts[node])
        return result

    def __repr__(self):
        return f"GCounter(counts={self.counts}, value={self.value()})"

nodes = ["replica_A", "replica_B", "replica_C"]
ra = GCounter("replica_A", nodes)
rb = GCounter("replica_B", nodes)

# Offline increments
ra.increment(5)   # replica A increments 5 times
rb.increment(3)   # replica B increments 3 times

print(f"Before merge: A={ra.value()}, B={rb.value()}")  # A=5, B=3

merged_at_a = ra.merge(rb)
merged_at_b = rb.merge(ra)

print(f"After merge: A sees {merged_at_a.value()}, B sees {merged_at_b.value()}")
# Both: 8 — correct! 5 + 3 = 8
```

## PN-Counter (Increment/Decrement Counter)

```python
class PNCounter:
    def __init__(self, node_id: str, all_nodes: list):
        self.node_id = node_id
        self.p = GCounter(node_id, all_nodes)  # increments
        self.n = GCounter(node_id, all_nodes)  # decrements

    def increment(self, amount: int = 1):
        self.p.increment(amount)

    def decrement(self, amount: int = 1):
        self.n.increment(amount)

    def value(self) -> int:
        return self.p.value() - self.n.value()

    def merge(self, other: "PNCounter") -> "PNCounter":
        result = PNCounter(self.node_id, list(self.p.counts.keys()))
        result.p = self.p.merge(other.p)
        result.n = self.n.merge(other.n)
        return result

# Example: distributed "likes" counter
pn_a = PNCounter("node_A", ["node_A", "node_B"])
pn_b = PNCounter("node_B", ["node_A", "node_B"])

pn_a.increment(10)  # 10 likes on node A
pn_b.increment(7)   # 7 likes on node B
pn_a.decrement(2)   # 2 unlikes on node A

merged = pn_a.merge(pn_b)
print(f"Total likes: {merged.value()}")  # 15 (10+7-2)
```

## OR-Set (Observed-Remove Set)

Add/remove sets naively conflict (add on A, remove on B concurrently — what wins?). OR-Set uses unique tags per add so removes are precise.

```typescript
type Tag = string;

class ORSet<T> {
  private elements: Map<string, Set<Tag>> = new Map();

  private elementKey(item: T): string {
    return JSON.stringify(item);
  }

  add(item: T, tag: Tag): void {
    const key = this.elementKey(item);
    if (!this.elements.has(key)) this.elements.set(key, new Set());
    this.elements.get(key)!.add(tag);
  }

  remove(item: T): void {
    this.elements.delete(this.elementKey(item));
  }

  has(item: T): boolean {
    const tags = this.elements.get(this.elementKey(item));
    return (tags?.size ?? 0) > 0;
  }

  merge(other: ORSet<T>): ORSet<T> {
    const result = new ORSet<T>();
    const allKeys = new Set([...this.elements.keys(), ...other.elements.keys()]);
    for (const key of allKeys) {
      const tagsA = this.elements.get(key) ?? new Set<Tag>();
      const tagsB = other.elements.get(key) ?? new Set<Tag>();
      const merged = new Set([...tagsA, ...tagsB]);
      if (merged.size > 0) result.elements.set(key, merged);
    }
    return result;
  }
}

const setA = new ORSet<string>();
const setB = new ORSet<string>();
setA.add("apple", "tag-001");  // add on replica A
setB.remove("apple");           // remove on replica B
const merged = setA.merge(setB);
console.log(merged.has("apple")); // true — add wins (surviving tag)
```

