```typescript
// Coordinator: route writes to correct replicas
class KVCoordinator {
  private ring: ConsistentHashRing;
  private replicationFactor: number;

  constructor(nodes: string[], replicationFactor = 3) {
    this.ring = new ConsistentHashRing(nodes);
    this.replicationFactor = replicationFactor;
  }

  // Get the N nodes responsible for this key
  getReplicaNodes(key: string): string[] {
    const primaryNode = this.ring.getNode(key);
    const allNodes = this.ring.getAllNodes();
    const primaryIndex = allNodes.indexOf(primaryNode);
    const replicas: string[] = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < this.replicationFactor; i++) {
      replicas.push(allNodes[(primaryIndex + i) % allNodes.length]);
    }
    return replicas;
  }

  async write(key: string, value: string, writeQuorum: number): Promise<boolean> {
    const replicas = this.getReplicaNodes(key);
    const acks = await Promise.allSettled(
      replicas.map(node => this.writeToNode(node, key, value))
    );
    const successCount = acks.filter(r => r.status === "fulfilled").length;
    return successCount >= writeQuorum; // W=2: succeed if 2+ nodes ack
  }

  async read(key: string, readQuorum: number): Promise<string | null> {
    const replicas = this.getReplicaNodes(key);
    const results = await Promise.allSettled(
      replicas.map(node => this.readFromNode(node, key))
    );
    const successes = results
      .filter(r => r.status === "fulfilled")
      .map(r => (r as PromiseFulfilledResult<any>).value);
    if (successes.length < readQuorum) throw new Error("Quorum not reached");
    // Return newest version (by timestamp or version vector)
    return successes.sort((a, b) => b.version - a.version)[0]?.value ?? null;
  }

  private async writeToNode(node: string, key: string, value: string): Promise<void> {
    // gRPC call to storage node
  }
  private async readFromNode(node: string, key: string): Promise<any> {
    // gRPC call to storage node
  }
}
```

### Step 5: Production Hardening Checklist

| Feature | Why Needed | Implementation |
|---------|-----------|----------------|
| Bloom filters | Avoid disk reads for missing keys | 10 bits/key, 1% false positive |
| Write-ahead log | Crash recovery without data loss | Flush to disk before MemTable |
| Compaction | Reclaim space, merge SSTables | Background thread, leveled or size-tiered |
| Merkle tree anti-entropy | Detect + repair replica divergence | Run during off-peak hours |
| Hinted handoff | Handle temporarily downed replicas | Store hint on coordinator, replay on recovery |
| Gossip protocol | Cluster membership, failure detection | Phi-accrual detector, 1s interval |
| Rate limiting | Prevent hotspot nodes from overwhelming | Token bucket per key prefix |

## Interview Q&A

**Q: How do you handle hot keys (celebrity problem)?**
A: Detect hot keys with frequency sketching (Count-Min Sketch, O(1) space). Mitigate: local in-memory cache on coordinators for top-N keys, key splitting (append random suffix, merge on read), or dedicated replica group for hot keys.

**Q: How does Cassandra decide which node handles a write without a master?**
A: Any node can be a coordinator for any write. The coordinator uses the consistent hash ring to determine the responsible replicas and sends the write to them. No single master — any node can coordinate any operation.

**Q: What is write amplification, and why does it matter?**
A: Write amplification = actual bytes written to disk / logical bytes written. LSM-tree compaction rewrites data multiple times across levels. RocksDB typical write amplification: 10-30x. At 1GB/s logical writes, actual disk writes are 10-30 GB/s — drives disk wear and I/O budget.

## Connection Pooling — Why Raw Connections Kill Databases

### The Cost of a Database Connection

A PostgreSQL connection consumes:
- **5–10 MB RAM** on the database server per connection
- **~5 ms** to establish (TCP handshake + auth + SSL)
- A **dedicated backend process** on the database

With 500 app servers × 20 connections each = **10,000 connections**:
- Memory: 10,000 × 7 MB = **70 GB** just for connections
- PostgreSQL starts degrading above **300–500 connections** due to lock contention

### How Connection Pooling Works

```mermaid
graph LR
    App1["App Server 1<br/>(pool: 5 connections)"]
    App2["App Server 2<br/>(pool: 5 connections)"]
    App3["App Server 3<br/>(pool: 5 connections)"]
    PgBouncer["PgBouncer<br/>65 server connections"]
    DB[("PostgreSQL<br/>65 backend processes")]
    App1 --> PgBouncer
    App2 --> PgBouncer
    App3 --> PgBouncer
    PgBouncer --> DB
    style PgBouncer fill:#e67e22,color:#fff
```

**PgBouncer** multiplexes thousands of client connections onto a small pool of actual server connections. In transaction-mode pooling, a server connection is only held for the duration of a single transaction.

### Sizing the Connection Pool

```python
# PostgreSQL connection pool sizing
def optimal_pool_size(cpu_cores: int, disk_type: str = "ssd") -> dict:
    if disk_type == "hdd":
        pool = cpu_cores * 2 + 4  # HDDs benefit from more parallel IO
    else:
        pool = cpu_cores * 2 + 1  # SSDs: IO is not the bottleneck
    return {
        "recommended_pool_size": pool,
        "max_connections_safe": pool * 3,
        "warning_threshold": pool * 10,
    }

# 32-core PostgreSQL instance on NVMe SSD
sizing = optimal_pool_size(cpu_cores=32, disk_type="ssd")
print(sizing)
# {'recommended_pool_size': 65, 'max_connections_safe': 195, 'warning_threshold': 650}
```

